ce:section.ce:para:
The elemental composition of the as-prepared BCNs and BN is investigated using an energy dispersive spectrometer (Table 1
                     ). It was found that all the samples composed of four elements (B, C, N, O). The BCN-1 contains the most carbon, and the BN contains the least. Such a difference in carbon content can influence the electronic structure of the catalysts. In order to study this effect, The XPS spectra of the BCN-1 and BN were collected. A broad asymmetric band was detected in the B 1s spectrum of the BCN-1 (Fig. 4
                     A), and it could be deconvoluted into two bands at 190.1 and 191.5 eV, corresponding to the B–N and B–O bonds, respectively [76]. It was noticed that the B–O bonding structure could be the residue from the H3BO3 due to its higher dissociation energy than B–N bonding structure (D°298K(B–O) = 809 kJ/mol, D°298K(B–N) = 378 kJ/mol) [77,78]. Compared with the B 1s spectrum of BN (Fig. 4C), the B–N bonding structure in the BCN-1 has lower binding energy, indicating higher electron density on the boron atom of the BCN-1.

Affected by the porous structure, the catalytic efficiency of the BCNs for the removal of sulfur compounds were different (Fig. 6
                     A). The porous-abundant BCN-1 exhibited the highest efficiency, which could achieve a sulfur removal of 98.2% in 4 h at 125 °C using dioxygen as the oxidant. Besides, the BCN-2 could also achieve ultra-deep desulfurization in 8 h. However, the porous-insufficient BCN-3 could only achieve a sulfur removal of 65.5% in 8 h. This higher activity for the BCN-1 was attributed to its abundant mesopores, which give better mass transfer between the catalyst and the substrate in the reaction. Moreover, the increased number of active zigzag edges in the BCN-1 should also facilitate the activation of dioxygen accelerating the oxidation of DBT. To make a further comparison, the catalytic activity of several aerobic ODS catalysts under similar conditions was listed (Table 2
                     ). As seen, the as-prepared metal-free BCN-1 exhibited an impressive catalytic activity for the oxidation of DBT. Notably, it was found the BCN-1 had a higher catalytic rate than reported BN catalysts (Entry 7–9), indicating that the carbon doping significantly enhanced the catalytic performance of BCN-1.
